strnlght@netcom.com (David Sternlight) writes:

> >512 -what-? 512 bits? 512 decimal digits? Length of what? Of the
> >moduli or of the primes that construct them?

> Give me a break. 512-bit primes are what pgp and Ripem use as a common
> alternative, and you certainly know that. No need for a make-wrong nit-pick
> here.

In your original message (which you wisely "forgot" to quote), you are
NOT specifying that you mean 512-bit moduli. I (and most others who
are using PGP) use 1024-bit moduli. I listed all the possibilities,
because otherwise you could accuse me of "mind-reading" - one of your
favorite arguments.

> >And you must try all of them, in order to factor a 1024-bit number by
> >trial and error.

> Not reading again, Vesselin? I wasn't talking about a factoring attack, but
> a massive key generation enterprise.

So what's the difference? In order to be able to factor 1024-bit
mnumbers, your "enterprise" must generate all possible 512-bit (or
less) primes. This is equivalent to factoring a number by brute force.
In fact, there -are- brute-force factoring algorithms (for relatively
small numbers only), which rely on huge collections of consecutive
prime numbers kept on a tape. This doesn't make the method different
from brute-force factoring - in order to be able to break -any- key,
you must generate -all- possible 512-bit prime numbers.

> >> Cracking messages then becomes trivial. They simply look up the
> >> corresponding secret key to any given public key on their list, and read
> >> everything.
> >
> >Trivial? Bullshit. How do you "simply look up" in a table of 10^150
> >entries? This more than the number of atoms in the known Universe.

> Is "bullshit" a technical comment you derive from the best rational
> arguments of mathematics and physics, or a novel logical step you've
> invented yourself?

It's just a colorful description of your claim that cracking messages
this way becomes trivial.

